Ut enim qui dat alteri consilium, aut eum hortatur ut hoc vel illud faciat, declarat quid ab eo cupiat fieri, non tamen eum ut id faciat obliyat, sed nec obli- gare intendit: haud aliter Leyislator ea lege, qua nihil sub- dito praecipit, sed tantum ostendit quid ab eo sub propositae poenoe conditione fieri velit, praesumendus est non habuisse voluntatem eum ulterius obliyandi quam ad propositam poenam. Quia si intentionem habuisset obligandi et ad culpam, facilli- mum ei fuisset, addita duntaxat praeceptione suam illam inten- tionem significare. Ergo cum nec simplex et mida ordinatio ex se obliget ad culpam, nec possit additio poenae temporalis ex se obligare nisi ad poenam temporalem subeundam; mani- festum est Leyem pure poenalem, quae praeter ista duo (sim- plicem dico ordinationem, et adjectam poenam temporalem,) nihil in se continet, quorum neutrum est obliyatorium ad culpam, non posse ex se ad culpam, sed ad paenam tantum obligare. Et est simile de Leyibus quas vocant conventiona- libus : quo exemplo libentius utor, quod conclusionem nostram non confirmet mod0, sed et egregie illustret. Cui etiam addi possit Tea-tatoris Voluntas ; et alia nonnulla, quorum est (quod ad obliyandi vim saltem attinet) ratio omnino consimilis. Incolae alicujus villae, qui condendi leyes proprie dictas potes- tate carent, in curia domini manerii (sic enim ex usu forensi loquendum est) aut alias extra curiam, de rebus quibusdam ad pacem et justitiam inter vicinos conservandam conducenti-

for the good management of a neighbourhood. If, for instance, it be there agreed that every householder shall in the month of May, give three days' labour to mending the roads3 and if he fail, be fined twenty pence for each day, (the price of a day’s labour being tenpenee 3) it is plain that the persons so eontracting intended that the householders should give their labour, for if not, they would not have made the fine double the value of the labour: but it is also plain that they did not intend to bind each other except to the extent of the fine, if any one could not or would not give his labour.

So if in a testament, (for a testament is a kind of Law, binding the executor and the legatees‚) we have “Caius appoints that Gaia, his wife, as long as she remains unmarried‚ shall keep a certain property; but if she marries again, shall forfeit it;'’ it is plain that Caius wished his wife not to marry again ; for that was the obJect of the condition: but he does not, nor can, intend to bind her to abstain from marrying under fault, so that if she marry again she is culpable.
